<BaseLayout
  title="Learn to Cook"
  description="A practical approach to cooking without recipes. The framework, not the formulas."
>
  <div class="container">
    <h1>Learn to Cook</h1>
    <p class="muted">
      Recipes are useful. Knowing how cooking actually works is more useful.
    </p>

    <h2>The 4-stage framework</h2>
    <p>
      Most savoury dishes follow the same shape:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Base.</strong> Onion, shallot, leek — something soft and sweet to start.</li>
      <li><strong>Flavour.</strong> Garlic, ginger, chilli, spice — added once the base is soft.</li>
      <li><strong>Body.</strong> The bulk of the dish — vegetables, beans, grains, sauce.</li>
      <li><strong>Balance.</strong> Acid, salt, fat, sweetness. Taste, adjust, taste again.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      Once you see this shape, most "what shall I cook" panic disappears. You're
      not following a recipe — you're filling in a template.
    </p>

    <h2>The four flavour levers</h2>
    <p>If a dish doesn't taste right, it's almost always one of these:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Salt.</strong> Bland? Add salt first. Always.</li>
      <li><strong>Acid.</strong> Heavy or flat? Lemon, vinegar, lime.</li>
      <li><strong>Fat.</strong> Thin or sharp? Olive oil, butter, yoghurt.</li>
      <li><strong>Sweet.</strong> Aggressive? A pinch of sugar, or roasted veg.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Coming soon</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Knife skills (the three you actually need)</li>
      <li>The pantry — what's worth keeping in</li>
      <li>How to cook without measuring</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
